632	Cloud 9	https://cf.geekdo-images.com/thumb/img/FwViEqj2cdpsoYjonJpeo9ne0_M=/fit-in/200x150/pic1229626.jpg	https://cf.geekdo-images.com/original/img/k13wU5yVvsBjLdFeFEAsk_bZToE=/0x0/pic1229626.jpg	Cloud 9 - The Daring Game of Ups and Downs\n\nPlayers earn points by daring to stay in the basket of a hot air balloon as it rises. Points increase as the balloon climbs from cloud to cloud, but so does the risk of the balloon falling. Should you jump out to save your points or trust that the pilot will take you safely higher?\n\nEveryone places their passenger token into the balloon's basket to start the trip, and receives a hand of six balloon cards. Then, each turn, a different "pilot" rolls an increasing number of specialized dice to see if the balloon can stay aloft. The dice dictate how many of the balloon cards are needed of each color. (There are also optionally played Wild Cards to keep everyone guessing.) Each player decides whether they think the pilot will have the cards to successfully take the balloon up, or whether they should jump out and keep the points earned so far. If they stay, they run the risk of getting no points if the pilot fails. If the balloon does fall, it is placed back on the lowest cloud. Everyone hops aboard and draws one new card, and the next trip begins. When a player earns 50 points the game is over.\n\n	30	20	30	1999	3	6	6	Aaron Weissblum
633	Elixir	https://cf.geekdo-images.com/thumb/img/DtKBBLhbLOfPHBMl2QSmM6SyBec=/fit-in/200x150/pic3567.jpg	https://cf.geekdo-images.com/original/img/IweK9vlfQZ4fZdnr0_3coMM-igw=/0x0/pic3567.jpg	Players collect ingredients cards in order to cast spells, and the first player to get rid of all of their spells wins the game.  So far so good.  The bad news is, the cards require between 1 and 4 ingredients.  Spells requiring 3 or 4 ingredients might actually help you win the game.  Spells requiring 1 or 2 ingredients cause another player to perform a forfeit, e.g proposing to another player.\n\nExpanded by\n\n    Elixir:  Alambic\n    Elixir: Mandragore\n    Elixir: Alchimie\n\n\n\n\n	60	60	60	1997	3	8	6	Sylvie Barc
634	River Dragons	https://cf.geekdo-images.com/thumb/img/MYEIkNERpIzdsEX8OkWJvWWyC88=/fit-in/200x150/pic1374907.jpg	https://cf.geekdo-images.com/original/img/R55rdH6lCERPaXz5XXsAhor-WEc=/0x0/pic1374907.jpg	In Dragon Delta, you want to move your pawn over a system of bridge-like planks to the other side of the board. An easy task! Or at least it would be if everyone were working together, but alas you're not. Instead you're all working on your own right next to one another, each convinced that your way is best.\n\nIn game terms, players simultaneously select five action cards to be performed from the nine actions available and lay them down in order they are to be played. The turn is then resolved one card at a time. The actions allow players to place plank foundations, place planks, move their pawns, cancel other players' actions, or remove planks or foundation stones. As can be expected for a design with simultaneous action selection, the game is rather chaotic.\n\nThe 2012 edition of the game, River Dragons, includes a double-sided game board not present in earlier editions, with one side of the board featuring rock piles on which you place stones (as in the original Dragon Delta), while the other side has a featureless river on which players can place stones in any location.\n\n	30	30	30	2000	2	6	4	Roberto Fraga
