es 4 mounted maps, and many scenarios that are each given their own scenario cards (ala the US Squad Leader wargame). Includes slightly larger counters than are usually used in Japanese wargames.\n\nThere was an expansion/sequel to this produced.\n\n	120	120	120	1984	2	2	2	Yasunori Sekiyama
6197	The Sun of Austerlitz	https://cf.geekdo-images.com/thumb/img/DFf8Ct1tpzw89WmVtLjORWTgThs=/fit-in/200x150/pic23392.jpg	https://cf.geekdo-images.com/original/img/ovbdCwkZYagnjUxrXyNwdrM4dHk=/0x0/pic23392.jpg	THE SUN OF AUSTERLITZ \n\nNapoleon's campaign in Moravia 1805\n\nComponents: One 22 x 34" map, 280 counters, 20 pages of rules, 7 player aid charts for setup and organization displays. November-December 1805.\n\nMap covers the territory from Znaim and Brunn to Olmutz and Ostrava, with the regular 2 miles to the hex. And it can mate with the "1809" map (Victory Games), allowing for a precession of the campaign through Durrenstein and Znaim.\n\nThe campaign scenario begins on 15 November, with the Russians retiring on Brünn and the French in pursuit. A second scenario begins with the French spread out around Brünn and the Coalition forces in Olmütz. Fortunately for Napoleon, the Allies attacked, but what if they had not? With the imminent entry of Prussia into the war, Napoleon would have been forced to advance on Olmütz, and his forces would have been beyond their LOC.\n\nDetailing Napoleon's campaign in Moravia, 1805, Sun of Austerliz is the only game to simulate the whole campaign at the operational level (2 mi/2 days/1,000 men) from the Fall of Vienna through the actions of Hollabrunn, Schoengrabern, and Wischau, to Austerlitz.\n\nGAME SYSTEM: CAMPAIGNS System - Series 1X = \n- scale = 3,200m/hex, \n- time = 2 days/turn\n- strength = 1,000 men/SP, .\n\n	120	120	120	2003	2	2	2	Kevin Zucker
6159	Dragon Quest Dungeon	https://cf.geekdo-images.com/thumb/img/HcHKt4mxr3gvfrHVy6kjNXxcviA=/fit-in/200x150/pic23112.jpg	https://cf.geekdo-images.com/original/img/azjrG75FLq0cfcitTcYRQDll26I=/0x0/pic23112.jpg	This game is a fantasy based game with strong gameplay ties to Battleship.\n\nEach player secretly sets up his own dungeon; there's a stand-up cut-out castle to use as a shield between the players. You place the square-shaped walls all over the place in your dungeon, along with stairwells to the smaller 2nd level of the dungeon. You also place your monsters and various treasures for the other player to discover, fake treasures (mimics) and your boss monster. You cannot place the weapons in such a way that they're impossible to get to (either cut off by walls or the boss monster). Your then tell the other player which space the entrance to the dungeon is.\n\nEach player in turn calls out the space he wishes to move to. You must call out each space one at a time. If there is a wall there, the player's turn ends. If the space is clear, they may continue on. If there is a monster, it must be fought. If the player is victorious, he gains a reward card for defeating it and may continue on; otherwise his turn ends. If there is a treasure chest, the player may examine it. If it's a treasure, he may keep it and move on. If its a mimic (a monster that looks like a treasure chest), then he must fight it as if it was a monster.\n\nPlay alternates between players until one player gets all 3 necessary treasures and then fights and kills the boss monster; that player is the winner.\n\nThere is minimal text on the components; as long as one player knows the rules and what the cards do, it is easy to show the other player (the cards with JPN text on them have distinctive pictures to make it easy to remember once told what it does)..\n\n	60	60	60	1990	2	2	2	(Uncredited)
